  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Inscription After the Record of the Fishing Village
  author: Jung Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Master Kwon Ka-won composed a record for Kong Baek-gong, and in it he painted forth a fishing village as if it truly existed. Though Baek-gong served as a court official, he took the name Fishing Village—a mark of where his joy resides. Yet Baek-gong does not merely cherish this joy within his heart; he gives it voice. Each time he raises his cup, he sings the "Song of the Fisherman"—not bound by the formal modes, not constrained by musical ratios, yet high and low notes respond to one another, and the melody flows in perfect harmony. This surely springs from nature itself.

    So it is: Baek-gong delights in the fishing village, Ka-won delights in Baek-gong's delight. And I, Do-jeon, listening to Baek-gong's song and reading Ka-won's record, find something that gently stirs within my heart. Should I claim that I too delight in the joy of these two men, would that not also be true?

    Alas, standing between heaven and earth, this body of mine is but a single grain of millet in the vast blue sea. Let me dwell with these two friends, seeing this world as drifting clouds, moving through rivers and lakes as an empty boat. In the end, who truly knows the source of such joy? Ah, how subtle and profound this feeling is!

    Sam-bong Jung Do-jeon, called Jong-ji, writes this at the Pavilion of River and Moon.
  footnotes:
    - Sam-bong (三峯, 'Three Peaks') is Jung Do-jeon's pen name, derived from the three peaks of a mountain landscape.
    - The 'Song of the Fisherman' (漁父詞) was a popular lyric form in East Asian poetry, often expressing themes of freedom and detachment from worldly concerns.
    - The metaphors of 'drifting clouds' and the 'empty boat' draw from Daoist philosophy, suggesting a life free from attachments and social pretense.
